	<exercises>
 					<p><exercise><!-- xml:id="ex-" -->
						<statement>
						<aside><p> (Source: <xref ref="ref-PS" />, Chapter 4, Exercise 4.5.4) </p></aside>
						For each of the following matrices, find the inverse if possible.  If it doesn't exist, explain why.
						<ol cols = "2">
							<li>
								<m> \begin{bmatrix} 2 \amp 1 \\ -1 \amp 3 \end{bmatrix} </m> </li>
							<li>
								<m> \begin{bmatrix} 0 \amp 1 \\ 5 \amp 3 \end{bmatrix} </m> </li>
							<li>
								<m> \begin{bmatrix} 2 \amp 1 \\ 3 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix} </m> </li>
							<li>
								<m> \begin{bmatrix} 2 \amp 1 \\ 4 \amp 2 \end{bmatrix} </m> </li>
							<li>
								<m> \begin{bmatrix} 0 \amp 1  \amp 2 \\ 1 \amp 2 \amp 5 \end{bmatrix} </m> </li>
							</ol> 
				</statement>
						<hint xml:id="hint-how-to-find-inverse-matrix">
							To find the inverse of a matrix <m>A</m> of size <m>n\times n</m>, one writes down the augmented matrix
							<me>
								\matr{c|c}
									{A\amp I_{n}}
							</me>
							and then row-reduces. If the RREF of <m>A</m> is <m>I_{n}</m> (the identity matrix of size <m>n\times n</m>), so that the above augmented matrix becomes
							<me>
								\matr{c|c}
									{A\amp I_{n}}
								\overset{\text{row reduction}}{\longrightarrow}
									\matr{c|c}
									{I_{n}\amp B}
							</me>
							for some matrix <m>B</m>, then <m>B</m> is the inverse <m>A^{-1}</m> of <m>A</m>. If the RREF of <m>A</m> is not <m>I_{n}</m>, then <m>A</m> is not invertible.
						</hint>
						<solution>
							
							<ol>
							<li><solution>
								We will use the approach explained in <xref ref="hint-how-to-find-inverse-matrix"/>.
								<md><mrow>
									\matr{cc|cc}
									{
										2 \amp 1 \amp 1 \amp 0
										\\
										-1 \amp 3 \amp 0 \amp 1
									}
									\overset{R_{1}+2R_{2}}{\longrightarrow}
									\amp
									\matr{cc|cc}
									{
										2 \amp 1 \amp 1 \amp 0
										\\
										0 \amp 7 \amp 1 \amp 2
									}
								</mrow><mrow>
									\overset{-R_{2}+7R_{1}}{\longrightarrow}
									\amp
									\matr{cc|cc}
									{
										14 \amp 0 \amp 6 \amp -2
										\\
										0 \amp 7 \amp 1 \amp 2
									}
								</mrow><mrow>
									\overset{\frac{1}{14}R_{1}}{\underset{\frac{1}{7}R_{2}}{\longrightarrow}}
									\amp
									\matr{cc|cc}
									{
										1 \amp 0 \amp \frac{3}{7} \amp -\frac{1}{7}
										\\
										0 \amp 1 \amp \frac{1}{7} \amp \frac{2}{7}
									}.
								</mrow></md>
								We conclude that <m>\begin{bmatrix} 2 \amp 1 \\ -1 \amp 3 \end{bmatrix}^{-1} = \frac{1}{7}\begin{bmatrix} 3 \amp -1 \\ 1 \amp 2 \end{bmatrix}.</m>
							</solution></li>
							<li><solution>
								<md><mrow>
									\matr{cc|cc}
									{
										0 \amp 1 \amp 1 \amp 0
										\\
										5 \amp 3 \amp 0 \amp 1
									}
									\overset{R_{1}\leftrightarrow R_{2}}{\longrightarrow}
									\amp
									\matr{cc|cc}
									{
										5 \amp 3 \amp 0 \amp 1
										\\
										0 \amp 1 \amp 1 \amp 0
									}
									</mrow><mrow>
									\overset{-3R_{2}+R_{1}}{\longrightarrow}
									\amp
									\matr{cc|cc}
									{
										5 \amp 0 \amp -3 \amp 1
										\\
										0 \amp 1 \amp 1 \amp 0
									}
									</mrow>
									<mrow>
									\overset{\frac{1}{5}R_{1}}{\longrightarrow}
									\amp
									\matr{cc|cc}
									{
										1 \amp 0 \amp \frac{-3}{5} \amp \frac{1}{5}
										\\
										0 \amp 1 \amp 1 \amp 0
									}
									</mrow></md>
									We conclude that <m>\begin{bmatrix} 0 \amp 1 \\ 5 \amp 3 \end{bmatrix}^{-1}=\frac{1}{5}\begin{bmatrix} -3 \amp 1 \\ 5 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix}</m>.
								</solution></li>
							<li><solution>
								<md><mrow>\matr{cc|cc}
									{
										2 \amp 1 \amp 1 \amp 0
										\\
										3 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 1
									}
									\overset{R_{1}\leftrightarrow R_{2}}{\longrightarrow}
									\amp
									\matr{cc|cc}
									{
										3 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 1
										\\
										2 \amp 1 \amp 1 \amp 0
									}
								</mrow><mrow>
									\overset{-2R_{1}+3R_{2}}{\longrightarrow}
									\amp
									\matr{cc|cc}
									{
										3 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 1
										\\
										0 \amp 3 \amp 3 \amp -2
									}
								</mrow><mrow>
									\overset{\frac{1}{3}R_{1}}{\underset{\frac{1}{3}R_{2}}{\longrightarrow}}
									\amp
									\matr{cc|cc}
									{
										1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp \frac{1}{3}
										\\
										0 \amp 1 \amp 1 \amp -\frac{2}{3}
									}
								</mrow></md>
									We conclude that <m>\begin{bmatrix} 2 \amp 1 \\ 3 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix}^{-1} = \frac{1}{3}\begin{bmatrix} 0 \amp 1 \\ 3 \amp -2 \end{bmatrix}</m>.</solution></li>
							<li><solution>
								<md><mrow>\matr{cc|cc}
									{
										2 \amp 1  \amp 1 \amp 0
										\\
										4 \amp 2 \amp 0 \amp 1
									}
									\overset{-2R_{1}+R_{2}}{\longrightarrow}
									\amp
									\matr{cc|cc}
									{
										2 \amp 1  \amp 1 \amp 0
										\\
										0 \amp 0 \amp -2 \amp 1
									} 
								</mrow></md>We see that the left-hand side will not have the identity matrix as its RREF. Therefore, the matrix <m>\begin{bmatrix} 2 \amp 1 \\ 4 \amp 2 \end{bmatrix}</m> does not have an inverse. </solution></li>
							<li><solution>
								The matrix
								<m>\begin{bmatrix} 0 \amp 1  \amp 2 \\ 1 \amp 2 \amp 5 \end{bmatrix} </m> is not a square matrix, so it cannot be invertible.</solution></li>
							</ol>
						</solution>
						<answer>
							<ol>
							<li><answer>
								<m>\begin{bmatrix} 2 \amp 1 \\ -1 \amp 3 \end{bmatrix}^{-1} = \frac{1}{7}\begin{bmatrix} 3 \amp -1 \\ 1 \amp 2 \end{bmatrix}</m>
							</answer></li>
							<li><answer>
								<m>\begin{bmatrix} 0 \amp 1 \\ 5 \amp 3 \end{bmatrix}^{-1}=\frac{1}{5}\begin{bmatrix} -3 \amp 1 \\ 5 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix}</m>
								</answer></li>
							<li><answer>
								<m>\begin{bmatrix} 2 \amp 1 \\ 3 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix}^{-1} = \frac{1}{3}\begin{bmatrix} 0 \amp 1 \\ 3 \amp -2 \end{bmatrix}</m></answer></li>
							<li><answer>
								The matrix <m>\begin{bmatrix} 2 \amp 1 \\ 4 \amp 2 \end{bmatrix}</m> does not have an inverse. </answer></li>
							<li><answer>
								The matrix
								<m>\begin{bmatrix} 0 \amp 1  \amp 2 \\ 1 \amp 2 \amp 5 \end{bmatrix} </m> does not have an inverse.</answer></li>
							</ol>
						</answer>

				</exercise> </p>
					<p><exercise><!-- xml:id="ex-" -->
						<statement>
							<aside><p> (Source: <xref ref="ref-PS" />, Chapter 4, Exercise 4.5.6) </p></aside>
							Let <m> A </m> be a <m> 2 \times 2 </m> invertible matrix, with <m> A = \begin{bmatrix} a \amp b \\ c \amp d \end{bmatrix}. </m> Find a formula for <m> A^{-1} </m> in terms of <m> a,b,c,d. </m> 
						</statement>
						<hint>
							You can use <xref ref="hint-how-to-find-inverse-matrix"/>. Be careful not to divide by zero (you need to make a case distinction).
						</hint>
						<solution>
							We use the approach from <xref ref="hint-how-to-find-inverse-matrix"/>, i.e. we want to row-reduce the following augmented matrix:
							<md>
								<mrow>
									\matr{cc|cc}
									{
										a \amp b \amp 1 \amp 0
										\\
										c \amp d \amp 0 \amp 1
									}
								</mrow>
							</md>
							But we need to be careful not to divide by zero in the process.

							By assumption, the matrix <m>A</m> is invertible. In particular, according to <xref ref="hint-how-to-find-inverse-matrix"/>, the reduced row-echelon form of <m>A</m> is the identity matrix. Therefore, if <m>a=0</m>, then neither <m>c</m> nor <m>b</m> can be zero (because else the first column resp. row of <m>A</m> would be zero). This means that we can make a case distinction: Assume first that <m>a\neq 0</m>, so that multiplying a row by <m>a</m> is a valid row operation:
							<md>
								<mrow>
									\matr{cc|cc}
									{
										a \amp b \amp 1 \amp 0
										\\
										c \amp d \amp 0 \amp 1
									}
									\overset{aR_{2}}{\longrightarrow}
									\amp 
									\matr{cc|cc}
									{
										a \amp b \amp 1 \amp 0
										\\
										ac \amp ad \amp 0 \amp a
									}
								</mrow>
								<mrow>
									\overset{-cR_{1} + R_{2}}{\longrightarrow}
									\amp\matr{cc|cc}
									{
										a \amp b \amp 1 \amp 0
										\\
										0 \amp ad-bc \amp -c \amp a
									}
									.
								</mrow>
							</md>
							Since the RREF of <m>A</m> is the identity (by the assumption that <m>A</m> is invertible), we conclude that <m>\det(A) = ad-bc \neq 0</m>. We proceed:
							<md>
								<mrow>
									\matr{cc|cc}{
										a \amp b \amp 1 \amp 0
										\\
										0 \amp ad-bc \amp -c \amp a
									}
									\overset{\frac{1}{\det(A)}R_{2}}{\longrightarrow}
									\amp
									\matr{cc|cc}
									{
										a \amp b \amp 1 \amp 0
										\\
										0 \amp 1 \amp \frac{-c}{\det(A)} \amp \frac{a}{\det(A)}
									}
								</mrow>
								<mrow>
									\overset{-bR_{2}+R_{1}}{\longrightarrow}
									\amp
									\matr{cc|cc}
									{
										a \amp 0 \amp 1 + \frac{bc}{\det(A)} \amp \frac{-ab}{\det(A)}
										\\
										0 \amp 1 \amp \frac{-c}{\det(A)} \amp \frac{a}{\det(A)}
									}
								</mrow>
								<mrow>
									=\amp
									\matr{cc|cc}
									{
										a \amp 0 \amp \frac{ad}{\det(A)} \amp \frac{-ab}{\det(A)}
										\\
										0 \amp 1 \amp \frac{-c}{\det(A)} \amp \frac{a}{\det(A)}
									}
								</mrow>
								<mrow>
									\overset{\frac{1}{a}R_{1}}{\longrightarrow}
									\amp
									\matr{cc|cc}
									{
										1 \amp 0 \amp \frac{d}{\det(A)} \amp \frac{-b}{\det(A)}
										\\
										0 \amp 1 \amp \frac{-c}{\det(A)} \amp \frac{a}{\det(A)}
									}
									,
								</mrow>
							</md>
							where the last operation is valid since <m>a\neq 0</m>.	We conclude: If <m>A= \begin{bmatrix} a \amp b \\ c \amp d \end{bmatrix}</m> is invertible and <m>a\neq 0</m>, then <m>\det(A) \neq 0</m>, and <m>A^{-1} =\frac{1}{\det(A)} \begin{bmatrix} d \amp -b \\ -c \amp a \end{bmatrix}.</m>


							The case where <m>a=0</m> works similarly: As explained above, this implies that <m>c\neq 0</m> and <m>b\neq 0</m>. This allows us to do the following row operations:
							<md>
								<mrow>
									\matr{cc|cc}
									{
										a \amp b \amp 1 \amp 0
										\\
										c \amp d \amp 0 \amp 1
									}
									=
									\amp
									\matr{cc|cc}
									{
										0 \amp b \amp 1 \amp 0
										\\
										c \amp d \amp 0 \amp 1
									}
								</mrow>
								<mrow>
									\overset{ \frac{1}{c}R_{2}}{\underset{\frac{1}{b}R_{1}}{\longrightarrow}}
									\amp
									\matr{cc|cc}
									{
										0 \amp 1 \amp \frac{1}{b} \amp 0
										\\
										1 \amp \frac{d}{c} \amp 0 \amp \frac{1}{c}
									}
								</mrow>
								<mrow>
									\overset{R_{1}\leftrightarrow R_{2}}{\longrightarrow}
									\amp
									\matr{cc|cc}
									{
										1 \amp \frac{d}{c} \amp 0 \amp \frac{1}{c}
										\\
										0 \amp 1 \amp \frac{1}{b} \amp 0
									}
								</mrow>
								<mrow>
									\overset{-\frac{d}{c}R_{1}+R_{2}}{\longrightarrow}
									\amp
									\matr{cc|cc}
									{
										1 \amp 0 \amp -\frac{d}{c}\cdot \frac{1}{b} \amp \frac{1}{c}
										\\
										0 \amp 1 \amp \frac{1}{b} \amp 0
									}
									.
								</mrow>
							</md>
							In the case where <m>a=0</m>, we have found the inverse of <m>A</m> to be 
							<me>
								A^{-1}
								=
								\begin{bmatrix}
									-\frac{d}{c}\cdot \frac{1}{b} \amp \frac{1}{c}
									\\
									\frac{1}{b} \amp 0
								\end{bmatrix}
								=
								\frac{1}{-bc} 
								\begin{bmatrix}
									d \amp -b
									\\
									-c \amp a
								\end{bmatrix}
								=
								\frac{1}{\det (A)} 
								\begin{bmatrix}
									d \amp -b
									\\
									-c \amp a
								\end{bmatrix}.
							</me>
							All in all, we have shown:  If <m>A= \begin{bmatrix} a \amp b \\ c \amp d \end{bmatrix}</m> is invertible (where <m>a</m> is any value), then <m>\det(A) \neq 0</m>, and <m>A^{-1} =\frac{1}{\det(A)} \begin{bmatrix} d \amp -b \\ -c \amp a \end{bmatrix}.</m>
						</solution>
						<answer xml:id="eq-inverse-of-2-times-2-matrix">
							If <m> A = \begin{bmatrix} a \amp b \\ c \amp d \end{bmatrix}</m> is invertible, its inverse is given by
							<me>
									\begin{bmatrix} a \amp b \\ c \amp d \end{bmatrix}^{-1}
									=
									\frac{1}{ad-bc}
									\begin{bmatrix} d \amp -b \\ -c \amp a \end{bmatrix}
									.
							</me>
						</answer>
					</exercise></p>
					<p><exercise><!-- xml:id="ex-" -->
						<statement>
							<aside><p> (Source: <xref ref="ref-KK" />, Chapter 2, Exercise 2.1.44) </p></aside>
							Using the inverse of the matrix, find the solution to the systems:
							<ol>
								<li> <me> \begin{bmatrix} 2 \amp 4 \\ 1 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix}x \\ y \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 2 \end{bmatrix} </me></li>
								<li> <me> \begin{bmatrix} 2 \amp 4 \\ 1 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix}x \\ y \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix} </me></li>
								<li>
									<me> \begin{bmatrix} 2 \amp 4 \\ 1 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix}x \\ y \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} a \\ b \end{bmatrix}</me> 
									(give the solution in terms of <m> a </m> and <m> b </m>)
								</li>
							</ol>							
						</statement>
						<hint>
							It is easiest to use <xref ref="eq-inverse-of-2-times-2-matrix"/> to determine the inverse matrix.
						</hint>
						<hint>
							Note that, given an invertible matrix <m>A</m>, we can multiply the vector equation
							<me>
								A \vec{x} = \vec{y}
							</me>
							on the left by <m>A^{-1}</m>, which yields the equivalent equation:
							<me>
								\vec{x} = A^{-1}\vec{y}
								.
							</me>
						</hint>
						<solution>
							First, we determine the inverse of <m> \begin{bmatrix} 2 \amp 4 \\ 1 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix} </m> using <xref ref="eq-inverse-of-2-times-2-matrix"/>:
							<me>
								\begin{bmatrix} 2 \amp 4 \\ 1 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix}^{-1}
								=
								\frac{1}{2\cdot 1 - 4\cdot 1}
								\begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp -4 \\ -1 \amp 2 \end{bmatrix}
								=
								\frac{1}{2}
								\begin{bmatrix} -1 \amp 4 \\ 1 \amp -2 \end{bmatrix}
								.
							</me>
							<ol>
								<li>
								<solution>
									Note that
									<me>
										\begin{bmatrix} 2 \amp 4 \\ 1 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix}x \\ y \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 2 \end{bmatrix}
										\iff
										\begin{bmatrix}x \\ y \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 2 \amp 4 \\ 1 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix}^{-1}
										\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 2 \end{bmatrix}.
									</me>
									We compute:
									<me>
										\begin{bmatrix} 2 \amp 4 \\ 1 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix}^{-1}
										\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 2 \end{bmatrix}
										=
										\frac{1}{2}
										\begin{bmatrix} -1 \amp 4 \\ 1 \amp -2 \end{bmatrix}
										\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 2 \end{bmatrix}
										=
										\frac{1}{2}
										\begin{bmatrix} -1 + 4\cdot 2 \\ 1 - 2 \cdot 2 \end{bmatrix}
										=
										\begin{bmatrix} \frac{7}{2} \\ \frac{-3}{2} \end{bmatrix}
										.
									</me>
									The solution is therefore given by <m>\begin{bmatrix} x \\ y \end{bmatrix}=\begin{bmatrix} \frac{7}{2} \\ \frac{-3}{2} \end{bmatrix}.</m>
								</solution></li>
								<li><solution>
									Note that
									<me>\begin{bmatrix} 2 \amp 4 \\ 1 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix}x \\ y \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix} 
										\iff
										\begin{bmatrix}x \\ y \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 2 \amp 4 \\ 1 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix}^{-1}\begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix} .
									</me>
									We compute:
									<me>
										\begin{bmatrix} 2 \amp 4 \\ 1 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix}^{-1}\begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix}
										=
										\frac{1}{2}
										\begin{bmatrix} -1 \amp 4 \\ 1 \amp -2 \end{bmatrix}
										\begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix}
										=
										\frac{1}{2}
										\begin{bmatrix} -2 + 4\cdot 0 \\ 2 -2\cdot 0 \end{bmatrix}
										=
										\begin{bmatrix} -1 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix}
										.
									</me>
									The solution is therefore given by <m>\begin{bmatrix} x \\ y \end{bmatrix}=\begin{bmatrix} -1 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix}</m>.
								</solution></li>
								<li><solution>
									Just as before, we see that
									<me> \begin{bmatrix} 2 \amp 4 \\ 1 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix}x \\ y \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} a \\ b \end{bmatrix}
										\iff
									 \begin{bmatrix}x \\ y \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 2 \amp 4 \\ 1 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix}^{-1}\begin{bmatrix} a \\ b \end{bmatrix}.
									</me> 
									We compute:
									<me>
										\begin{bmatrix} 2 \amp 4 \\ 1 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix}^{-1}
										\begin{bmatrix} a \\ b \end{bmatrix}
										=
										\frac{1}{2}
										\begin{bmatrix} -1 \amp 4 \\ 1 \amp -2 \end{bmatrix}
										\begin{bmatrix} a \\ b \end{bmatrix}
										=
										\frac{1}{2}
										\begin{bmatrix} -a + 4 b \\ a - 2b \end{bmatrix}.
									</me> 
									The solution is therefore given by <m>\begin{bmatrix} x \\ y \end{bmatrix}=\begin{bmatrix} \frac{-a}{2} + 2 b \\ \frac{a}{2} - b \end{bmatrix}.</m>
								</solution></li>
							</ol>
						</solution>
						<answer>
							<ol>
								<li>
								<answer>
									<m>\begin{bmatrix} x \\ y \end{bmatrix}=\begin{bmatrix} \frac{7}{2} \\ \frac{-3}{2} \end{bmatrix}</m>
								</answer></li>
								<li><answer>
									<m>\begin{bmatrix} x \\ y \end{bmatrix}=\begin{bmatrix} -1 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix}</m>
								</answer></li>
								<li><answer>
									<m>\begin{bmatrix} x \\ y \end{bmatrix}=\begin{bmatrix} \frac{-a}{2} + 2 b \\ \frac{a}{2} - b \end{bmatrix}</m>
								</answer></li>
							</ol>
						</answer>
					</exercise></p>
					<p><exercise><!-- xml:id="ex-" -->
						<statement>
							<aside><p> (Source: <xref ref="ref-PS" />, Chapter 4, Exercise 4.5.1) </p></aside>
							For each of the following matrices, determine whether <m> B </m> is an inverse of <m> A. </m>
							<ol>
								<li> <me> A = \begin{bmatrix} 2 \amp 4 \\ 1 \amp 4 \end{bmatrix}, \ \ B = \frac{1}{2}\begin{bmatrix} 3 \amp -4 \\ -1 \amp 2 \end{bmatrix}. </me> </li>
								<li> <me> A = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp -2 \\ 4 \amp -7 \end{bmatrix}, \ \ B = \begin{bmatrix} -1 \amp 2 \\ -4 \amp 7 \end{bmatrix}. </me> </li>
								<li> <me> A = \begin{bmatrix} 4 \amp 1  \amp 3 \\ 2 \amp 1 \amp 2 \\ 1 \amp 0 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix}, \ \ B = \begin{bmatrix} 1  \amp -1 \amp -1  \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp -2 \\ -1 \amp 1 \amp 2 \end{bmatrix}. </me> </li>
							</ol>
						</statement>
						<hint>
							You can use <xref ref="eq-inverse-of-2-times-2-matrix"/> to find the inverse of a <m>2\times 2</m> matrix.
						</hint>
						<solution>
							In the situation of  <m>2\times 2</m> matrices, we can approach the question in two different ways: one option is using <xref ref="eq-inverse-of-2-times-2-matrix"/> to compute the inverse <m>A^{-1}</m> of <m>A</m> and then check whether it coincides with the given matrix <m>B</m>. The second option is to check whether <m>AB=I</m> and <m>BA=I</m>, which is exactly the case if <m>B=A^{-1}</m>. This latter approach also works for matrices of larger size.
							<ol>
								<li><solution>
									For this example, we use <xref ref="eq-inverse-of-2-times-2-matrix"/> to compute <m>A^{-1}</m>:
									<md>
										<mrow>
											A^{-1}
										=\amp
										\begin{bmatrix} 2 \amp 4 \\ 1 \amp 4 \end{bmatrix}^{-1}
										=
										\frac{1}{2\cdot 4 - 1\cdot 4}
										\begin{bmatrix} 4 \amp -4 \\ -1 \amp 2 \end{bmatrix}
									</mrow>
									<mrow>	=\amp
										\frac{1}{4}
										\begin{bmatrix} 4 \amp -4 \\ -1 \amp 2 \end{bmatrix}
										\neq
										\frac{1}{2}\begin{bmatrix} 3 \amp -4 \\ -1 \amp 2 \end{bmatrix}
										=
										B.</mrow>
									 </md>
									 We conclude that, no, <m>B</m> is not the inverse of <m>A</m>.
								</solution></li>
								<li><solution>
									For this example, we will actually check whether <m>B</m> behaves like the inverse of <m>A</m>, so we compute:
									<md><mrow> AB \amp=
										\begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp -2 \\ 4 \amp -7 \end{bmatrix}
										\begin{bmatrix} -1 \amp 2 \\ -4 \amp 7 \end{bmatrix}
									</mrow>
										<mrow>
										\amp=
										\begin{bmatrix}	1\cdot (-1) - 2 \cdot (-4) 
												\amp 	1 \cdot 2 - 2 \cdot 7
												\\
														4\cdot (-1) - 7 \cdot (-4) 
												\amp 	4 \cdot 2 - 7 \cdot 7	
										\end{bmatrix}
										=
										\begin{bmatrix}	7 \amp -12	\\ 24 \amp -41	\end{bmatrix}.
									</mrow>
									</md>
									Since <m>AB \neq I</m>, we conclude that, no, <m>B</m> is not the inverse of <m>A</m>. (We note that it was not necessary to compute all entries of <m>AB</m>; it suffices to see that its <m>(1,1)</m>-entry is not equal to <m>1</m>.)
								</solution></li>
								<li><solution>
									We compute:
									<md>
										<mrow>
											AB \amp=
											\begin{bmatrix} 4 \amp 1  \amp 3 \\ 2 \amp 1 \amp 2 \\ 1 \amp 0 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix}
											\begin{bmatrix} 1  \amp -1 \amp -1  \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp -2 \\ -1 \amp 1 \amp 2 \end{bmatrix}
										</mrow>
										<mrow>
											\amp=
											\begin{bmatrix} 4 +0 -3 \amp -4+1+3  \amp -4-2+6 \\ 2+0-2 \amp -2+1+2 \amp -2-2+4 \\ 1+0-1 \amp -1+0+1 \amp -1+0+2 \end{bmatrix}
											=
											\begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 0  \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix}.
										</mrow>
									</md>
									At this point, there is hope that <m>B</m> is the inverse of <m>A</m>, but we still need to check the other equation, so we compute:
									<md>
										<mrow>
											BA \amp=											
											\begin{bmatrix} 1  \amp -1 \amp -1  \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp -2 \\ -1 \amp 1 \amp 2 \end{bmatrix}
											\begin{bmatrix} 4 \amp 1  \amp 3 \\ 2 \amp 1 \amp 2 \\ 1 \amp 0 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix}
										</mrow>
										<mrow>
											\amp=
											\begin{bmatrix} 4-2-1 \amp  1-1+0  \amp 3-2-1 \\ 0+2-2  \amp 0+1+0 \amp 0+2-2  \\  -4+2+2 \amp -1+1+0 \amp -3+2+2  \end{bmatrix}
											=
											\begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 0  \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix}.
										</mrow>
									</md>
									We conclude that, indeed, <m>B</m> is the inverse of <m>A</m>.
							</solution></li>
							</ol>
						</solution>
						<answer>
							<ol>
								<li><answer>No.</answer></li>
								<li><answer>No.</answer></li>
								<li><answer>Yes.</answer></li>
							</ol>
						</answer>
					</exercise></p>

					<p><exercise xml:id="ex-prod-of-invertible-matrices">
						<statement>
							<aside><p> (Source: <xref ref="ref-KK" />, Chapter 2, Exercise 2.1.50) </p></aside>
							Suppose <m>A, B</m> are two invertible matrices of the same size. Show that <m> (AB)^{-1} = B^{-1}A^{-1} </m> by verifying that 
							<me> A B (B^{-1}A^{-1}) =I \quad\text{and}\quad B^{-1}A^{-1} (AB) =I. </me>
						</statement>
						<!-- <hint>
						</hint> -->
						<solution>
							Recall that <m>A^{-1}</m> is the unique matrix that satisfies <m>AA^{-1}=I=A^{-1}A</m>, and similarly for <m>B^{-1}</m>. We use this in the following computation:
							<md>
								<mrow>
									A B (B^{-1}A^{-1})
									\amp=
									A (B B^{-1})A^{-1}
									\amp \text{by associativity of matrix multiplication}
								</mrow>
								<mrow>
									\amp=
									A (I)A^{-1}
									\amp \text{since } B B^{-1}=I
								</mrow>
								<mrow>
									\amp=
									A A^{-1}
									\amp \text{by the properties of } I
								</mrow>
								<mrow>
									\amp=
									I
									\amp\text{since } AA^{-1} = I.
								</mrow>
							</md>
							For the other equality, we proceed similarly:
							<md>
								<mrow>
									B^{-1}A^{-1} (AB)
									\amp=
									B^{-1}(A^{-1} A)B
									\amp \text{by associativity of matrix multiplication}
								</mrow>
								<mrow>
									\amp=
									B^{-1}(I)B
									\amp \text{since } A^{-1}A=I
								</mrow>
								<mrow>
									\amp=
									B^{-1}B
									\amp \text{by the properties of } I
								</mrow>
								<mrow>
									\amp=
									I
									\amp\text{since } B^{-1}B=I.
								</mrow>
							</md>
							</solution>
					</exercise></p>


					<p><exercise xml:id="ex-sums-of-inverses-of-matrices">
						<statement>
							<aside><p> (Source: <xref ref="ref-KN" />, Chapter 2, Exercise 2.4.41) </p></aside>
							Let <m> A </m> and <m> B </m> denote <m> n \times n </m> invertible matrices.
							<ol>
								<li> <p>Show that <m> A^{-1} + B^{-1}  = A^{-1}(A + B) B^{-1}. </m></p>
								<p><hint>
									Recall that, for a matrix <m>A</m>, its inverse <m>A^{-1}</m> is <em>uniquely</em> determined by satisfying the property <m>AA^{-1}=I</m> and <m>A^{-1}A=I</m>. This means: If a matrix <m>C</m> satisfies <m>AC=I</m> and <m>CA=I</m>, then <m>C=A^{-1}</m>.
								</hint></p>
									<p><solution>
										By substracting <m>B^{-1}</m> from each side of the equation, we see that the claim is equivalent to showing that <m> A^{-1}  = A^{-1}(A + B) B^{-1} - B^{-1}. </m> Recall that <m>A^{-1}</m> is the unique matrix that satisfies both <m>AA^{-1}=I</m> and <m>A^{-1}A=I</m>, so it suffices to show that  <m>A^{-1}(A + B) B^{-1} - B^{-1}</m> has this property. We compute (using Theorem 2.1.1 in Section 2.1 of <xref ref="ref-KN"/>):
										<md>
											<mrow>
												\amp A \bigl( A^{-1}(A + B) B^{-1} - B^{-1} \bigr)
												\amp
											</mrow>
											<mrow>
												\quad\amp=
												AA^{-1}(A + B) B^{-1} - AB^{-1} 
												\amp\text{by distributivity}
											</mrow>
											<mrow>
												\quad\amp=
												I(A + B) B^{-1} - AB^{-1} 												
												\amp\text{by the properties of } A^{-1}
											</mrow>
											<mrow>
												\amp
												=
												I(AB^{-1} + BB^{-1}) - AB^{-1}											
												\amp\text{by distributivity}
											</mrow>
											<mrow>
												\quad\amp=
												AB^{-1} + BB^{-1} - AB^{-1}												
												\amp\text{by the properties of } I
											</mrow>
											<mrow>
												\amp
												=
												AB^{-1} + I - AB^{-1}												
												\amp\text{by the properties of } B^{-1}
											</mrow>
											<mrow>
												\quad\amp=
												I.
											</mrow>
										</md>
										Similarly,
										<md>
											<mrow>
												\amp\bigl( A^{-1}(A + B) B^{-1} - B^{-1} \bigr) A
											</mrow>
											<mrow>
												\quad\amp=
												A^{-1}(A + B) B^{-1}A - B^{-1}A
												\amp\text{by distributivity}
											</mrow>
											<mrow>
												\quad\amp=
												(A^{-1}A + A^{-1}B) B^{-1}A - B^{-1}A
												\amp\text{by distributivity}
											</mrow>
											<mrow>
												\amp
												=
												(I + A^{-1}B) B^{-1}A - B^{-1}A
												\amp\text{by the properties of } A^{-1}
											</mrow>
											<mrow>
												\quad\amp=
												IB^{-1}A + A^{-1}BB^{-1}A - B^{-1}A
												\amp\text{by distributivity}
											</mrow>
											<mrow>
												\quad\amp=
												B^{-1}A + A^{-1}IA  - B^{-1}A
												\amp\text{by the properties of } I \text{ and } B^{-1}
											</mrow>
											<mrow>
												\quad\amp=
												A^{-1}A 
												=
												I
												\amp\text{by the properties of } A^{-1}.
											</mrow>
										</md>
										We have checked that the matrix <m> A^{-1}(A + B) B^{-1} - B^{-1} </m> indeed satisfies the defining property of <m>A^{-1}</m>.
									</solution></p>
								</li>
								<li> <p>If <m> A + B </m> is also invertible, show that <m> A^{-1} + B^{-1} </m> is invertible and find a formula for <m> (A^{-1} + B^{-1})^{-1}. </m></p>
									<p><hint>Use the first part of the exercise. Then use <xref ref="ex-prod-of-invertible-matrices"/>.</hint></p>
									<p><solution>
										By assumption, <m>C:= A + B </m> is invertible. By the first part of the exercise, we know that <m> A^{-1} + B^{-1}  = A^{-1}(A + B) B^{-1},</m> i.e. <m>A^{-1} + B^{-1}= A^{-1}CB^{-1}.</m> The matrix <m>A^{-1}CB^{-1}</m> is invertible as product of invertible matrices by <xref ref="ex-prod-of-invertible-matrices"/>, which shows that <m>A^{-1} + B^{-1}</m> is invertible. <xref ref="ex-prod-of-invertible-matrices"/> also gives a formula for the inverse of a product, which we use for the equalities <m>(*)</m> in the following computation:
										<md>
											<mrow>
												(A^{-1}CB^{-1})^{-1} 
												\amp=(A^{-1}[CB^{-1}])^{-1}
												\overset{(*)}{=}[CB^{-1}]^{-1} (A^{-1})^{-1}
											</mrow>
											<mrow>
												\amp\overset{(*)}{=}(B^{-1})^{-1} C^{-1} A
												=B C^{-1} A.
											</mrow>
										</md>
										We conclude: The inverse of <m> A^{-1} + B^{-1} </m> is given by <m>B C^{-1} A = B (A + B)^{-1} A.</m>
									</solution></p>
									<p><answer>The inverse of <m> A^{-1} + B^{-1} </m> is given by <m>B (A + B)^{-1} A.</m></answer></p>
								</li>
							</ol>
						</statement>
					</exercise></p>
					<p><exercise><!-- xml:id="ex-" -->
						<statement>
							<aside><p> (Source: <xref ref="ref-KN" />, Chapter 2, Exercise 2.5.2) </p></aside>
							In each case, find the elementary matrix <m> E </m> such that <m> B = EA. </m>
							<ol>
								<li>
									<me> A =\begin{bmatrix} 2 \amp 1 \\ 3 \amp -1 \end{bmatrix},
										\ \ B = \begin{bmatrix} 2 \amp 1 \\ 1 \amp -2 \end{bmatrix} </me>

									<solution>
										We see that <m>A \overset{-R_{1} + R_{2}}{\longrightarrow}B</m>, so the row operation is of type III. This means:
										<me>
											B = EA
											\ \text{ where } \
											E
											=
											\begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 0 \\ -1 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix}.
										</me>
									</solution>
									<answer>
										<me>
											E
											=
											\begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 0 \\ -1 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix}.
										</me>
									</answer>
								</li>
								<li>
									<me> A =\begin{bmatrix} -1 \amp 2 \\ 0 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix},
									\ \ B = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp -2 \\ 0 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix} </me>
									<solution>
										We see that <m>A \overset{(-1)R_{1}}{\longrightarrow}B</m>, so the row operation is of type I. This means:
										<me>
											B = EA
											\ \text{ where } \
											E
											=
											\begin{bmatrix} -1 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix}.
										</me>
									</solution>
									<answer>
										<me>
											E
											=
											\begin{bmatrix} -1 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix}.
										</me>
									</answer>
								</li> 
								<li> <me> A = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 1 \\ -1 \amp 2 \end{bmatrix}, \ \ B = \begin{bmatrix} -1 \amp 2 \\ 1 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix} </me>
									<solution>
										We see that <m>A \overset{R_{1}\leftrightarrow R_{2}}{\longrightarrow}B</m>, so the row operation is of type II. This means:
										<me>
											B = EA
											\ \text{ where } \
											E
											=
											\begin{bmatrix} 0 \amp 1 \\ 1 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix}.
										</me>
									</solution>
									<answer>
										<me>
											E
											=
											\begin{bmatrix} 0 \amp 1 \\ 1 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix}.
										</me>
									</answer>
								</li>
								<li>
									<me> A =\begin{bmatrix} 4 \amp 1 \\ 3 \amp 2 \end{bmatrix}, \ \ B = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp -1 \\ 3 \amp 2 \end{bmatrix} </me>

									<solution>
										We see that <m>A \overset{-R_{2}+R_{1}}{\longrightarrow}B</m>, so the row operation is of type III. This means:
										<me>
											B = EA
											\ \text{ where } \
											E
											=
											\begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp -1 \\ 0 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix}.
										</me>
									</solution>
									<answer>
										<me>
											E
											=
											\begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp -1 \\ 0 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix}.
										</me>
									</answer>
								</li>
								<li>
									<me> A =\begin{bmatrix} -1 \amp 1 \\ 1 \amp -1 \end{bmatrix}, \ \ B = \begin{bmatrix} -1 \amp 1 \\ -1 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix} </me>

									<solution>
										We see that <m>A \overset{(-1)R_{2}}{\longrightarrow}B</m>, so the row operation is of type I. This means:
										<me>
											B = EA
											\ \text{ where } \
											E
											=
											\begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp -1 \end{bmatrix}.
										</me>
									</solution>
									<answer>
										<me>
											E
											=
											\begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp -1 \end{bmatrix}.
										</me>
									</answer>
								</li>
								<li>
									<me> A =\begin{bmatrix} 2 \amp 1 \\ -1 \amp 3 \end{bmatrix}, \ \ B = \begin{bmatrix} -1 \amp 3 \\ 2 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix} </me>
									<solution>
										We see that <m>A \overset{R_{1}\leftrightarrow R_{2}}{\longrightarrow}B</m>, so the row operation is of type II. This means:
										<me>
											B = EA
											\ \text{ where } \
											E
											=
											\begin{bmatrix} 0 \amp 1 \\ 1 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix}.
										</me>
									</solution>
									<answer>
										<me>
											E
											=
											\begin{bmatrix} 0 \amp 1 \\ 1 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix}.
										</me>
									</answer>
								</li>
							</ol>
						</statement>
						<hint xml:id="hint-elementary-matrices">
							Recall the three different types of elementary row operations from <xref ref="hint-row-operations"/>. Each of them corresponds to left-multiplication by an elementary matrix <m>E</m>:
							<hint>
								The row operation <m>R_{k}\leftrightarrow R_{l}</m> corresponds to multiplication on the left with the matrix <m>[e_{i,j}]</m>, where
							 	<md>
							 		<mrow>
							 		e_{k,l} \amp= 1 = e_{l,k},
							 		</mrow>
							 		<mrow>
							 		e_{i,i} \amp=
							 		\left\{
							 			\begin{array}{2}
							 				1 \amp\amp \text{if } i\neq k \text{ and } i \neq l,
							 				\\
							 				0 \amp\amp \text{if } i= k \text{ or } i = l,
							 			\end{array}
							 		\right.
							 		</mrow>
							 		<mrow>
							 		e_{i,j} \amp= 0 \text{ for all remaining } i,j .
								 	</mrow>
							 	</md>
							 	We define elementary matrices of this type to be <em>of type I</em>.
							</hint>
							<hint>
								The row operation <m>\alpha R_{k}</m> where <m>\alpha</m> is a non-zero number corresponds to multiplication on the left with the matrix <m>[e_{i,j}]</m>, where
								<md>
									<mrow>
							 		e_{i,j} \amp=
							 		\left\{
							 			\begin{array}{2}
							 				1 \amp\amp \text{if } i=j\neq k,
							 				\\						 				
							 				\alpha \amp\amp \text{if } i=j= k, \text{ and}
							 				\\
							 				0 \amp\amp \text{if } i\neq j.
							 			\end{array}
							 		\right.
							 		</mrow>
								</md>
								We define elementary matrices of this type to be <em>of type II</em>.
							</hint>
							<hint>
								The row operation <m>\alpha R_{k} + R_{l}</m> corresponds to multiplication on the left with the matrix <m>[e_{i,j}]</m>, where
								<md>
									<mrow>
							 		e_{i,j} \amp=
							 		\left\{
							 			\begin{array}{2}
							 				1 \amp\amp \text{if } i=j,
							 				\\						 				
							 				\alpha \amp\amp \text{if } i=l \text{ and } j=k, \text{ and}
							 				\\
							 				0 \amp\amp \text{for all remaining } i, j.
							 			\end{array}
							 		\right.
							 		</mrow>
								</md>
								We define elementary matrices of this type to be <em>of type III</em>.
							</hint>						
						</hint>
					</exercise></p>
						<p><exercise><!-- xml:id="ex-" -->
						<statement>
							<aside><p> (Source: <xref ref="ref-KK" />, Chapter 2, Exercise 2.1.59) </p></aside>
							Let <m> A = \begin{bmatrix}  1 \amp 2 \amp 1 \\ 0 \amp 5 \amp 1 \\ 2 \amp -1 \amp 4 \end{bmatrix}. </m>
							<!--  Suppose a row operation is applied to <m> A </m>  and the result is-->
							and <m> B  = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 2 \amp 1 \\ 0 \amp 5 \amp 1 \\ 1 \amp -\frac{1}{2} \amp 2 \end{bmatrix}.</m>
							<ol>
								<li> Find the elementary matrix <m> E </m> such that <m> EA = B. </m></li>
								<li> Find the inverse of <m> E, E^{-1},</m> such that <m> E^{-1}B = A. </m> </li>
							</ol>
						</statement>
						<hint>
							Look into <xref ref="hint-elementary-matrices"/> for the different types of elementary matrices.
						</hint>
						<solution>
							We see that <m>A\overset{\frac{1}{2}R_{3}}{\longrightarrow}B</m>, so the row operation is of type I. This means that
							<me>
								B = EA
								\ \text{ where } \
								E
								=
								\begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp \frac{1}{2}  \end{bmatrix}.
							</me>
							In particular, <m>B\overset{2R_{3}}{\longrightarrow}A</m> undoes this operation, so that 
							<me>
								E^{-1}
								=
								\begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 2 \end{bmatrix}.
							</me>					
						</solution>
						<answer>
							<ol>
								<li> <m> E=\begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp \frac{1}{2}  \end{bmatrix} </m></li>
								<li> <m> E^{-1}=\begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 2 \end{bmatrix}</m> </li>
							</ol>
						</answer>
					</exercise></p>

						<p><exercise><!-- xml:id="ex-" -->
						<statement>
							<aside><p> (Source: <xref ref="ref-PS" />, Chapter 4, Exercise 4.5.2) </p></aside>
							Suppose <m> AB = AC </m> and <m> A </m> is an invertible <m> n \times n </m> matrix.  Does it follow that <m> B = C? </m> Explain why or why not.
						</statement>
						<!-- <hint>
						</hint> -->
						<solution>
							By assumption, <m>A^{-1}</m> exists. In particular, we can multiply the equation <m> AB = AC </m> on the left by <m>A^{-1}</m> and we get <m>A^{-1}AB = A^{-1}AC </m>. Recall that <m>A^{-1}</m> has the property that <m>A^{-1}A=I</m>, so our equation can be rewritten as <m>IB=IC</m>. Since <m>I</m> has the property <m>B=IB</m> and <m>C=IC</m>, we conclude that, indeed, <m> B = C. </m>
						</solution>
						<answer>
							Yes, <m> B = C. </m>
						</answer> 
					</exercise></p>
					<p><exercise><!-- xml:id="ex-" -->
						<statement>
							<aside><p> (Source: <xref ref="ref-PS" />, Chapter 4, Exercise 4.5.3) </p></aside>
							Suppose <m> AB = AC </m> and <m> A </m> is a non-invertible <m> n \times n </m> matrix.  Does it follow that <m> B = C? </m> Explain why or why not.
						</statement>
						<!-- <hint>
						</hint> -->
						<solution>
							Suppose <m>A=0</m>, the matrix all of whose entries are <m>0</m>. Then for <em>any</em> matrix <m>B</m>, we have <m>AB=0</m>. In particular, <m>AB=AC</m> for <em>all</em> matrices <m>B, C</m>. This shows that <m> AB = AC </m> does not necessarily imply <m> B = C </m>.
						</solution>
						<answer>
							No, <m> B</m> is not necessarily equal to <m>C</m>.
						</answer>
					</exercise></p>
					<p><exercise><!-- xml:id="ex-" -->
						<statement>
							<aside><p> (Source: <xref ref="ref-RB" />, Chapter Matrix Inverses, Exercise MISLE.T10) </p></aside>
							Construct an example to demonstrate that <m> (A + B)^{-1} = A^{-1} + B^{-1} </m> is not true for all invertible square matrices <m> A </m> and <m> B </m> of the same size.  
						</statement>
						<hint>
							It is possible to choose <m>A=B</m> to be a very nice matrix.
						</hint>
						<solution>
							We choose <m>A=B=I</m>, so that
							<me>
								(A + B)^{-1} = (2I)^{-1} = \frac{1}{2}I^{-1} = \frac{1}{2}I,
							</me>
							while
							<me>
								A^{-1} + B^{-1} = 2 I^{-1} = 2 I.
							</me>
							This shows that <m>(A + B)^{-1}</m> does not equal <m>A^{-1} + B^{-1}</m>.
						</solution>
						<answer>
							The equality is not true for <m>A=B=I</m>.
						</answer>
					</exercise></p>
					<p><exercise><!-- xml:id="ex-" -->
						<statement>
							<aside><p> (Source: <xref ref="ref-KK" />, Chapter 2, Exercise 2.1.40) </p></aside>
							Let 
							<me> A = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 2 \amp 3 \\ 2 \amp 1 \amp 4 \\ 1 \amp 0 \amp 4 \end{bmatrix}. </me>
							Find <m> A^{-1} </m> if possible.  If <m> A^{-1} </m> does not exist, explain why.    
						</statement>
						<hint>
							See <xref ref="hint-how-to-find-inverse-matrix"/> for an algorithm to find <m>A^{-1}</m>, if it exists.
						</hint>
						<solution>
							We compute
							<md>
								<mrow>
									\matr{ccc|ccc}
									{
										1 \amp 2 \amp 3 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 0
										\\
										2 \amp 1 \amp 4 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 0
										\\
										1 \amp 0 \amp 4 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 1
									}
									\overset{-2R_{1}+R_{2}}{\underset{-R_{1}+R_{3}}{\longrightarrow}}
									\amp\matr{ccc|ccc}
									{
										1 \amp 2 \amp 3 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 0
										\\
										0 \amp -3 \amp -2 \amp -2 \amp 1 \amp 0
										\\
										0 \amp -2 \amp 1 \amp -1 \amp 0 \amp 1
									}
								</mrow>
								<mrow>
									\overset{-2R_{2}+3R_{3}}{\longrightarrow}
									\amp\matr{ccc|ccc}
									{
										1 \amp 2 \amp 3 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 0
										\\
										0 \amp -3 \amp -2 \amp -2 \amp 1 \amp 0
										\\
										0 \amp 0 \amp 7 \amp 1 \amp -2 \amp 3
									}
								</mrow>
							</md>
							From this, we can already see that the matrix is invertible. We continue:
							<md>
								<mrow>
									\matr{ccc|ccc}
									{
										1 \amp 2 \amp 3 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 0
										\\
										0 \amp -3 \amp -2 \amp -2 \amp 1 \amp 0
										\\
										0 \amp 0 \amp 7 \amp 1 \amp -2 \amp 3
									}
									\overset{\frac{1}{7}R_{3}}{\underset{2R_{3}'+R_{2}}{\longrightarrow}}
									\amp\matr{ccc|ccc}
									{
										1 \amp 2 \amp 3 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 0
										\\
										0 \amp -3 \amp 0 \amp \frac{-12}{7} \amp \frac{3}{7} \amp \frac{6}{7}
										\\
										0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp \frac{1}{7} \amp \frac{-2}{7} \amp \frac{3}{7}
									}
								</mrow>								
								<mrow>
									\overset{-\frac{1}{3}R_{2}}{\underset{-3R_{3}+R_{1}}{\longrightarrow}}
									\amp\matr{ccc|ccc}
									{
										1 \amp 2 \amp 0 \amp \frac{4}{7} \amp \frac{6}{7} \amp \frac{-9}{7}
										\\
										0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp \frac{4}{7} \amp \frac{-1}{7} \amp \frac{-2}{7}
										\\
										0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp \frac{1}{7} \amp \frac{-2}{7} \amp \frac{3}{7}
									}
								</mrow>
								<mrow>
									\overset{-2R_{2}+R_{1}}{\longrightarrow}
									\amp\matr{ccc|ccc}
									{
										1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp \frac{-4}{7} \amp \frac{8}{7} \amp \frac{-5}{7}
										\\
										0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp \frac{4}{7} \amp \frac{-1}{7} \amp \frac{-2}{7}
										\\
										0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp \frac{1}{7} \amp \frac{-2}{7} \amp \frac{3}{7}
									}.
								</mrow>
							</md>
							We conclude that <m>A^{-1}=
							\frac{1}{7}
							\begin{bmatrix} -4 \amp 8 \amp -5 \\ 4 \amp -1 \amp -2 \\ 1 \amp -2 \amp 3 \end{bmatrix}</m>
						</solution>
						<answer>
							<m>A^{-1}=
							\frac{1}{7}
							\begin{bmatrix} -4 \amp 8 \amp -5 \\ 4 \amp -1 \amp -2 \\ 1 \amp -2 \amp 3 \end{bmatrix}</m>.
						</answer>
					</exercise></p>
					<p><exercise><!-- xml:id="ex-" -->
						<statement>
							<aside><p> (Source: <xref ref="ref-KN" />, Chapter 2, Exercise 2.4.17) </p></aside>
							If <m> c \ne 0, </m> find the inverse of <m>A=\begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp -1 \amp 1 \\ 2 \amp -1 \amp 2 \\ 0 \amp 2 \amp c \end{bmatrix}</m> in terms of <m> c. </m>      
						</statement>
						<hint>
							See <xref ref="hint-how-to-find-inverse-matrix"/> for an algorithm to find <m>A^{-1}</m>, if it exists.
						</hint>
						<solution>
							We use <xref ref="hint-how-to-find-inverse-matrix"/>, i.e. we will row-reduce the augmented matrix <m>\matr{c|c}{A\amp I_{3}}</m>:
							<md>
								<mrow>
									\matr{ccc|ccc}
									{
										1 \amp -1 \amp 1 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 0
										\\
										2 \amp -1 \amp 2 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 0
										\\
										0 \amp 2 \amp c  \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 1
									}
									\overset{-2R_{1}+R_{2}}{\longrightarrow}
									\amp\matr{ccc|ccc}
									{
										1 \amp -1 \amp 1 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 0
										\\
										0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp -2 \amp 1 \amp 0
										\\
										0 \amp 2 \amp c  \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 1
									}
								</mrow>
								<mrow>
									\overset{-2R_{2}+R_{3}}{\underset{R_{2}+R_{1}}{\longrightarrow}}
									\amp\matr{ccc|ccc}
									{
										1 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp -1 \amp 1 \amp 0
										\\
										0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp -2 \amp 1 \amp 0
										\\
										0 \amp 0 \amp c  \amp 4 \amp -2 \amp 1
									}.
								</mrow>
							</md>
							Since <m>c\neq 0</m>, dividing by <m>c</m> is a valid row-operation, so that
							<md>
								<mrow>
									\matr{ccc|ccc}
									{
										1 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp -1 \amp 1 \amp 0
										\\
										0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp -2 \amp 1 \amp 0
										\\
										0 \amp 0 \amp c  \amp 4 \amp -2 \amp 1
									}
									\overset{\frac{1}{c}R_{3}}{\longrightarrow}
									\amp\matr{ccc|ccc}
									{
										1 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp -1 \amp 1 \amp 0
										\\
										0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp -2 \amp 1 \amp 0
										\\
										0 \amp 0 \amp 1  \amp \frac{4}{c} \amp \frac{-2}{c} \amp \frac{1}{c}
									}
								</mrow>
								<mrow>
									\overset{-R_{3}+R_{1}}{\longrightarrow}
									\amp\matr{ccc|ccc}
									{
										1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp -1-\frac{4}{c} \amp 1+\frac{2}{c} \amp \frac{-1}{c}
										\\
										0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp -2 \amp 1 \amp 0
										\\
										0 \amp 0 \amp 1  \amp \frac{4}{c} \amp \frac{-2}{c} \amp \frac{1}{c}
									}.
								</mrow>
							</md>
							We conclude that
							<me>
								A^{-1}
								=
								\begin{bmatrix}
									-1-\frac{4}{c} \amp 1+\frac{2}{c} \amp \frac{-1}{c} \\ -2 \amp 1 \amp 0 \\ \frac{4}{c} \amp \frac{-2}{c} \amp \frac{1}{c}
								\end{bmatrix}
								=
								\frac{1}{c}
								\begin{bmatrix}
									-c-4 \amp c+2 \amp -1 \\ -2c \amp c \amp 0 \\ 4 \amp -2 \amp 1
								\end{bmatrix}
								.
							</me>
						</solution>
						<answer>
							<me>
								A^{-1}
								=
								\frac{1}{c}
								\begin{bmatrix}
									-c-4 \amp c+2 \amp -1 \\ -2c \amp c \amp 0 \\ 4 \amp -2 \amp 1
								\end{bmatrix}
								.
							</me>
						</answer>
					</exercise></p>
				</exercises>